jk","Latchford, Cheshire, England":"Latchford, Cheshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1284–":"about 1284–Deceased","1284–Male":"1284–Deceased","1288–Female":"1288–Deceased","1344–1393":"1344–1393","1350–1398":"1350–1398","1258–Male":"1258–Deceased","1262–Female":"1262–Deceased","about 1309":"about 1309","Abt 1284":"about 1284","about 1283":"about 1283","1258":"1258","1344":"1344","1398":"1398","1288":"1288","1350":"1350","1262":"1262","1284":"1284","1393":"1393","Lachinginbank, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Cotton near Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England, United Kingdom","Latchford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Latchford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","Latchford, Cheshire, England":"Latchford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Cotton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of numerous places called from Old English <i>(æt) cotum</i> (dative plural of <i>cot</i>) ‘at the cottages or huts’ (or sometimes possibly from a Middle English plural, <i>coten</i>). Examples include Coton (Cambridgeshire, Northamptonshire, Staffordshire), Cottam (East Yorkshire, Lancashire, Nottinghamshire), and Cotham (Nottinghamshire). Particularly common in Staffordshire.","French: from a pet form of the personal name <i>Nicolas</i> (see   Nicholas  ), derived via <i>Nicot</i>, or of the personal name   Jacques  , derived via <i>Jacot</i>.","History: John Cotton (1584–1652) was a noted Puritan preacher, who landed at Boston, MA, from London in 1633 and became leader of the Congregationalists in America."],"variants":[{"name":"Cotten","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Cotton  .","Altered form of German <b>Kotten</b>, a habitational name from any of several places so named in Rhineland, Westphalia, Silesia, etc., or perhaps an American shortened form of composite German surnames such as <b>Kottenhagen</b>, <b>Kottenhoff</b>, <b>Kottenkamp</b> (see   Koth  )."]},{"name":"Nicholas","meanings":["English (southwestern England and south Wales) and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Nicholas</i> (from Latin <i>Nicolaus</i>, from Greek <i>Nikolaos</i>, from <i>nikān</i> ‘to conquer’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’). Forms with <i>-ch-</i> are due to hypercorrection (compare   Anthony  ). The name in various vernacular forms was popular among Christians throughout Europe in the Middle Ages, largely as a result of the fame of a 4th-century Lycian bishop, about whom a large number of legends grew up, and who was venerated in the Orthodox Church as well as the Catholic. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages and also their patronymics and other derivatives, e.g. Croatian and Serbian <b>Nikolić</b> (see   Nikolic  ), Greek <b>Papanikolaou</b> ‘(son of) Nicholas the priest’ and   Nikolopoulos  . Compare   Nickolas  .","History: The colonial official and revolutionary patriot Robert Carter Nicholas was from a prominent VA family on both sides. His father was a British navy surgeon who emigrated <i>c.</i> 1700 from Lancashire, England, to Williamsburg, VA."]},{"name":"Cotham","meanings":["English (Lancashire and Yorkshire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottom","meanings":["English (Lancashire): variant of   Cotton  ."]},{"name":"Cottam","meanings":["English (Midlands and northern England): variant of   Cotton  ."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Cotton was born about 1284, in Latchford, Warrington, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, Hugh Cotton, was 28 and his mother, Mrs. Hugh Cotton, was 24. He married Cicely Lostock about 1309, in Latchford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. He died in Latchford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1284–":"umbes 1284–Surnud","1284–Male":"1284–Surnud","1288–Female":"1288–Surnud","1344–1393":"1344–1393","1350–1398":"1350–1398","1258–Male":"1258–Surnud","1262–Female":"1262–Surnud","about 1309":"umbes 1309","Abt 1284":"umbes 1284","about 1283":"umbes 1283","1258":"1258","1344":"1344","1398":"1398","1288":"1288","1350":"1350","1262":"1262","1284":"1284","1393":"1393","Lachinginbank, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Cotton near Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Latchford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Latchford, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Latchford, Cheshire, England":"Latchford, Cheshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1284–":"noin 1284–Kuollut","1284–Male":"1284–Kuollut","1288–Female":"1288–Kuollut","1344–1393":"1344–1393","1350–1398":"1350–1398","1258–Male":"1258–Kuollut","1262–Female":"1262–Kuollut","about 1309":"noin 1309","Abt 1284":"noin 1284","about 1283":"noin 1283","1258":"1258","1344":"1344","1398":"1398","1288":"1288","1350":"1350","1262":"1262","1284":"1284","1393":"1393","Lachinginbank, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Cotton near Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, England":"Cambridge, Cambridgeshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Latchford, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom":"Latchford, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Latchford, Cheshire, England":"Latchford, Cheshire, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr"